# Estimation of Ruin Probability

## Define a function to simulate 1 path for a given time period

Here, $c_0$ is the initial surplus and $\theta$ is the relative security loading. 

```{r chunk1}

c0 <- 50
theta <- 0.07

```

We assume a Cramér-Lundberg model, where claim frequency follows a Poisson process with rate $\lambda$ and claims sizes are i.i.d. and independent of frequency. For $\text{Exponential} (c)$ and $\text{Gamma} (\gamma , c)$ we use the formulae 

$$
\mathbb E \left [ Y \right] = \frac{1}{c} \quad \text{and} \quad \mathbb E \left[ Y \right] = \frac{\gamma}{c}
$$
to calculate expected value. This allows us to find the premium rate $\pi = \lambda (1 + \theta) \mathbb E [Y]$, so that the surplus $C(t) = c_0 + \pi t - S(t)$ at any time $t$ can be determined by simulating $S(t) \sim \text{CompPois} (\lambda t, G)$ for various claim size distributions $G$. The probability of ruin at any time $t$ is thus 
$$
\psi_t(c_0) = P\left( \underset{s \leq t}{\inf} \ C(s) < 0 \, \bigg| \, C(0) = c_0 \right).
$$

```{r chunk2}

ruin_check <- function(t, lambda, sev_distribution, shape = NULL, rate, 
                       theta = 0.07) {
  
  # Calculate individual expected claim
  EY <- if (sev_distribution == "exponential") {
    1 / rate
  } else if (sev_distribution == "gamma") {
    shape / rate
  }
  # Premium rate
  pi = (1 + theta) * lambda * EY

  # Number of claims
  N <- rpois(1, lambda * t)
  if (N == 0) {
    return(c(FALSE, pi * t))
  }
  
  # Arrivals
  arrivals <- sort(runif(N, min = 0, max = t))
  
  # Claim size
  claims <- if (sev_distribution == 'exponential') {
              rexp(N, rate = rate)
            } else if (sev_distribution == 'gamma') {
              rgamma(N, shape = shape, rate = rate)
            }
  
  # Check for ruin
  surplus <- c0 + pi * arrivals - cumsum(claims)
  
  return(any(surplus < 0))
}

```

## MC Simulations

We can interpret the `ruin_check()` function as essentially an outcome of an indicator random variable, so if we have $n$ draws $I_1, \dots, I_n$ from `ruin_check()` then the sum
$$
\frac{I_1 + \dots + I_n}{n}
$$
is an estimator for the ruin probability. Furthermore, it's nice to know the expected profit under each scenario. This is given by 
$$
\pi t - \mathbb E \left [{S(t)} \right ] = \pi t - \lambda t \mathbb E [Y]. 
$$

```{r chunk3}

profit <- function(t, lambda, sev_distribution, shape = NULL, rate, theta = 0.07) {
  # Calculate individual expected claim
  EY <- if (sev_distribution == "exponential") {
    1 / rate
  } else if (sev_distribution == "gamma") {
    shape / rate
  }
  
  pi <- (1+ theta) * lambda * EY
  
  return(pi * t - lambda * t * EY)
}

```


