# Analysis of Reinsurance Products

## 5 Year Probability of Ruin under reinsurance options A and B

Under a reinsurance policy, the reinsurer pays some function of the claim amount $h(Y)$ whilst the insurer pays $Y - h(Y)$. The reinsurance company charges a reinsurance loading factor of $\xi = 0.1$, resulting in the reinsurance premium rate being $\pi_h = (1 + \xi)\lambda \mathbb E[h(Y)]$. The claim frequency $N(t)$ is unchanged, still distributed as $\text{Poisson}(\lambda t)$. Thus, the surplus under reinsurance at any time $t$ is 
$$
C(t) = c_0 + (\pi - \pi_h) t - \sum_{i = 1}^{N(t)} \left( Y_i - h(Y_i) \right).
$$

```{r chunk5}

xi <- 0.1

```

Define a function to return the expected retained loss for Gamma and Exponential distributions under different policies. The retained loss for $Y \sim \text{Gamma} (\gamma, c)$ under and EoL policy was calculated using the formula from Amin et al. 2022:
$$
\mathbb E\left[ Y  \wedge d \, \right] = \frac{\gamma}{c} F_{\gamma + 1, \, c}(d) + d \left( 1 - F_{\gamma, \, c}(d) \right)
$$
where $F_{\gamma, c} (\cdot)$ is the cdf of a gamma distribution with shape $\gamma$ and rate $c$. 

```{r chunk6}

policy_expectation <- function(sev_distribution, shape = NULL, 
                               rate, policy, d = NULL, alpha = NULL) {
  # Initialise
  EY_retained <- 0;
  EY_reinsurer <- 0;
  
  if (policy == 'proportional' && sev_distribution == 'exponential') {
    EY <- 1 / rate
    EY_retained <- alpha * 1 / rate
    EY_reinsurer <- EY - EY_retained
  } else if (policy == 'proportional' && sev_distribution == 'gamma') {
    EY <- shape / rate
    EY_retained <- alpha * shape / rate
    EY_reinsurer <- EY - EY_retained
  } else if (policy == 'EoL' && sev_distribution == 'exponential') {
    EY <- 1 / rate
    EY_retained <- (1 - exp(-rate * d)) / rate
    EY_reinsurer <- EY - EY_retained
  } else if (policy == 'EoL' && sev_distribution == 'gamma') {
    EY <- shape / rate
    EY_retained <- (shape / rate) * pgamma(d, shape = shape + 1, rate = rate) +
                    d * (1 - pgamma(d, shape = shape, rate = rate))
    EY_reinsurer <- EY - EY_retained
  }
  # return the total expected claim size, then insurer's, then reinsurer's
  return(c(EY, EY_retained, EY_reinsurer))
}

```

Define a function to check for ruin under each policy.

```{r chunk7}

ruin_check_reinsurance <- function(t, lambda, sev_distribution, shape = NULL, 
                                   rate, policy, d = NULL, alpha = NULL,
                                   c0 = 50, theta = 0.07, xi = 0.1) {
  
  # Find expectations of the reinsurer and insurer
  EY_all <- policy_expectation(sev_distribution = sev_distribution, shape = shape, 
                               rate = rate, policy = policy, d = d, alpha = alpha)
  
  # Premium rates
  pi_insurer <- (1 + theta) * lambda * EY_all[1]
  pi_reinsurer <- (1 + xi) * lambda * EY_all[3]
  pi <- pi_insurer - pi_reinsurer
  
  # Number of claims 
  N <- rpois(1, lambda * t)
  if (N == 0) {
    return(c(FALSE, pi * t))
  }
  
  # Sorted arrival times
  arrivals <- sort(runif(N, min = 0, max = t))
  
  # Claim sizes
  claims <- if (sev_distribution == 'exponential') {
    rexp(N, rate = rate)
  } else if (sev_distribution == 'gamma') {
    rgamma(N, shape = shape, rate = rate)
  }
  
  claims_retained <- if (policy == 'proportional') {
    alpha * claims
  } else if (policy == 'EoL') {
    pmin(claims, d)
  }
  
  # Check for ruin
  surplus <- c0 + pi * arrivals - cumsum(claims_retained)
  return(any(surplus < 0))
}

```

Also define a function to get the expected profit, given by 
$$
\pi_{\text{net}} t - \mathbb E [S(t)] = (\pi - \pi_h ) t - \lambda t \mathbb E [Y - h(Y)]. 
$$

```{r chunk8}

profit_reinsurance <- function(t, lambda, sev_distribution, shape = NULL, 
                               rate, policy, d = NULL, alpha = NULL,
                               c0 = 50, theta = 0.07, xi = 0.1) {
  
  # Find expectations of the reinsurer and insurer
  EY_all <- policy_expectation(sev_distribution = sev_distribution, shape = shape, 
                               rate = rate, policy = policy, d = d, alpha = alpha)
  
  # Premium rates
  pi_insurer <- (1 + theta) * lambda * EY_all[1]
  pi_reinsurer <- (1 + xi) * lambda * EY_all[3]
  pi <- pi_insurer - pi_reinsurer
  
  return(pi * t - lambda * t * EY_all[2])
}

```

