## Determining the Range of the Amount Retained and Deductible

We require that the insurer's net of reinsurance premium income per unit time $\pi_{\text{net}} = \pi - \pi_h$ be larger than the expected aggregate claims per unit time, to avoid certain ruin. This translates to the Net Profit Condition
$$
\pi - \pi_h = (1 + \theta) \lambda \mathbb E[Y] - (1 + \xi) \lambda \mathbb E[h(Y)] > \mathbb E[S(1)] = \lambda \mathbb E[Y - h(Y)].
$$
Rearranging this using the linearity of expectation, we get 
$$
\xi \, \mathbb E [h(Y)] < \theta \, \mathbb E[Y].
$$

Under option A, this becomes
$$
\alpha > 1 - \frac{\theta}{\xi},
$$
which simply evaluates to 
```{r chunk10}

alpha_min <- 1 - theta / xi
print(alpha_min)

```

So $\alpha$ is bounded by $0.3$. Under option B the inequality becomes
$$
\mathbb E [(Y - d)^+] < \frac{\theta}{\xi} \, \mathbb E [Y]. 
$$
Finding $d$ requires numerical computation, which is easier to implement if we rearrange this to 
$$
\frac{\mathbb E [(Y - d)^+]}{\mathbb E [Y]} < \frac{\theta}{\xi} = 0.7,
$$
so the problem is just finding $d$ such that
$$
f(d) = \frac{\mathbb E [(Y - d)^+]}{\mathbb E [Y]} - 0.7 < 0.
$$
```{r chunk11}

# Give a range of values for d:
d <- seq(0, 10, 0.0001)

# Define f(d)
d_function <- function(d) {
  E_all <- policy_expectation(sev_distribution = 'gamma', shape = 0.3162, 
                              rate = 0.229245, policy = 'EoL', d = d)
  return(E_all[3] / E_all[1] - 0.7)
}

d_ratio <- sapply(d, d_function)
plot(d, d_ratio, type = 'l')

# Compute the lower bound
d_min <- uniroot(d_function, lower = 0, upper = 10)$root
print(d_min)

```
Thus, the lower bound for $d$ is roughly $0.8036$. There is no upper bound since $f(d)$ is monotonically decreasing. We have 
$$
\alpha > 0.3 \quad \text{and} \quad d > 0.8036.
$$

## Maximising the Adjustment Coefficient Under Reinsurance Policy

The adjustment coefficient $R$ is given by the first positive solution of $r$ to the equation
$$
\mathbb E\left [e^{r(S(t) - \pi_{\text{net}} t )}\right] = 1. 
$$
In the Cramér-Lundberg model solving the above is equivalent to solving the Lundberg equation
$$
\lambda + \pi_{\text{net}} r - \lambda M_{Y - h(Y)}(r) = 
1 + r \Big( (1 + \theta) \mathbb E [Y] - (1 + \xi) \mathbb E [h(Y)] \Big) - M_{Y - h(Y)} (r)= 0.
$$
We require the two adjustment coefficients $R_A$ and $R_B$ for the two reinsurance options. Under option A the Lundberg equation becomes 
$$
1 + r \mathbb E[Y] \Big (1 + \theta - (1 + \xi)(1 - \alpha)\Big) - M_Y (\alpha r) = 0.
$$
Using the properties of $\text{Gamma} (\gamma, c)$ we obtain the relevant function to find the roots of: 
$$
f_A(r) = 1 + \frac{r \gamma}{c} \Big( 1 + \theta - (1 + \xi) (1 - \alpha)\Big) - \left( \frac{c}{c - \alpha r} \right)^\gamma.
$$
Finding the first positive solution of $f_A(r) = 0$ gives $R_A$. Under option B, the Lundberg equation becomes 
$$
1 + r \Big((1 + \theta) \mathbb E[Y] - (1 + \xi) \mathbb E[(Y - d)^+] \Big) - M_{Y - h(Y)} (r) = 0.
$$
Now, to find the mgf of $Y - h(Y) = \min(Y, d)$ we integrate:
$$
M_{Y - h(Y)} (r) = \mathbb E \left [ e^{r \min (Y , d)} \right] = \underbrace{\frac{c^\gamma}{\Gamma (\gamma)} \int_0^d y^{\gamma - 1} e^{-(c - r) y} \,dy}_{Y < d}
+ \underbrace{\frac{c^\gamma e^{rd}}{\Gamma (\gamma)} \int_d^\infty y^{\gamma - 1} e^{-cy} \, dy}_{Y \geq d}
$$
For the case where $Y < d$, letting $F_{\gamma, c} (\cdot)$ denote the cdf of $\text{Gamma} (\gamma ,c)$, the integral can be expressed as 
$$
\frac{c^\gamma}{\Gamma (\gamma)} \int_0^d y^{\gamma - 1} e^{-(c - r) y} \,dy = 
\left( \frac{c}{c - r}\right)^\gamma \frac{(c - r)^\gamma}{\Gamma (\gamma)} \int_0^d y^{\gamma - 1} e^{-(c - r) y} \,dy = 
\left( \frac{c}{c - r}\right)^\gamma F_{\gamma, c - r} (d). 
$$
where $c > r$. Similarly, for the case where $Y \geq d$, the integral can be expressed as
$$
\frac{c^\gamma e^{rd}}{\Gamma (\gamma)} \int_d^\infty y^{\gamma - 1} e^{-cy} \, dy = e^{rd} \Big( 1 - F_{\gamma, c} (d) \Big).
$$
Combining the two results yields
$$
M_{Y - h(Y)} (r) = \left( \frac{c}{c - r}\right)^\gamma F_{\gamma, c - r} (d) + e^{rd} \Big( 1 - F_{\gamma, c} (d) \Big).
$$
Therefore, to find $R_B$ we will find the first positive root of 
$$
f_B(r) = 1 + r \Big((1 + \theta) \mathbb E[Y] - (1 + \xi) \mathbb E[(Y - d)^+] \Big) - 
\left( \frac{c}{c - r}\right)^\gamma F_{\gamma, c - r} (d) - e^{rd} \Big( 1 - F_{\gamma, c} (d) \Big).
$$

```{r chunk12}

# Define the parameter values for scenario II
shape_param <- 0.3162
rate_param <- 0.229245

# Define a helper function for the EoL mgf
mgf_EoL <- function(r, d) {
  (rate_param / (rate_param - r))^shape_param * 
   pgamma(d, shape = shape_param, rate = rate_param - r) + 
          exp(r * d) * (1 - pgamma(d, shape = shape_param, rate = rate_param))
}

# Define f_A and f_B
r_function_A <- function(r, alpha, theta = 0.07, xi = 0.1) {
 1 + ( r * shape_param / rate_param) * (1 + theta - (1 + xi) * (1 - alpha)) - 
         (rate_param / (rate_param - alpha * r))^shape_param
}

r_function_B <- function(r, d, theta = 0.07, xi = 0.1) {
  E_EoL <- policy_expectation(sev_distribution = 'gamma', shape = shape_param, 
                              rate = rate_param, policy = 'EoL', d = d)
  1 + r * ((1 + theta) * E_EoL[1] - (1 + xi) * E_EoL[3]) - mgf_EoL(r, d)
}

# Define functions to find the roots
find_r_A <- function(alpha, theta = 0.07, xi = 0.1) {
  
  if (alpha <= 0) {
    return(NA)
  } 
  # Check if there's a root
  lower_bound <- 1e-6
  # There's singularities at these points
  upper_bound <- rate_param - 1e-8
  f_lower <- r_function_A(lower_bound, alpha, theta, xi)
  f_upper <- r_function_A(upper_bound, alpha, theta, xi)
  if (f_lower * f_upper > 0) {
    return(NA)
  }
  # Return the value
  uniroot(function(r) r_function_A(r, alpha, theta, xi), lower = lower_bound, 
          upper = upper_bound)$root
}

find_r_B <- function(d, theta = 0.07, xi = 0.1) {
    if (d <= 0) {
      return(NA)
    }
    # Check for roots
    lower_bound <- 1e-6
    upper_bound <- rate_param - 1e-8
    
    f_lower <- r_function_B(lower_bound, d, theta, xi)
    f_upper <- r_function_B(upper_bound, d, theta, xi)
    if (f_lower * f_upper > 0) {
      return(NA)
    }
    # Return the value
    uniroot(function(r) r_function_B(r, d, theta, xi), lower = lower_bound, 
            upper = upper_bound)$root
}

# Apply the functions
alpha_grid <- seq(alpha_min, 1, 0.0001)
d_grid <- seq(d_min, 5, 0.0001)
r_A_values <- sapply(alpha_grid, find_r_A)
r_B_values <- sapply(d_grid, find_r_B)

# Display results
plot(alpha_grid, r_A_values, type = 'l')
plot(d_grid, r_B_values, type = 'l')

R_A <- max(r_A_values, na.rm = TRUE)
R_B <- max(r_B_values, na.rm = TRUE)
alpha_max <- alpha_grid[which(r_A_values == R_A)]
d_max <- d_grid[which(r_B_values == R_B)]

# Find profits
alpha_max_profit <- profit_reinsurance(t = 60, lambda = 2, sev_distribution = 'gamma', 
                                       shape = 0.3162, rate = 0.229245, 
                                       policy = 'proportional', alpha = alpha_max)

d_max_profit <- profit_reinsurance(t = 60, lambda = 2, 
                                   sev_distribution = 'gamma', shape = 0.3162, 
                                   rate = 0.229245, policy = 'EoL', d = d_max)

adjustment_coefficient_summary <- data.frame(adjustment_coef = c(R_A, R_B), 
                                             optimal_policy = c(alpha_max, d_max), 
                                             upper_bound = c(exp(-c0 * R_A), 
                                                             exp(-c0 * R_B)), 
                                             profit = c(alpha_max_profit, 
                                                        d_max_profit))
adjustment_coefficient_summary <- as.data.frame(t(adjustment_coefficient_summary))
colnames(adjustment_coefficient_summary) <- c("A", "B")
print(adjustment_coefficient_summary)

```
# Target Survival Probability

We wish to tune the parameters $\alpha$ and $d$ such that the 5-year survival probability reaches $99\%$. We will find $\alpha_{99\%}$ and $d_{99\%}$ so that the estimated 5-year survival probability $\hat p = 1- \hat \psi_{60} (c_0)$ lies in $(0.9895,0.9905)$ with $95\%$ confidence. Therefore, we require the standard error of $\hat p$. Again, since we will estimate this probability using MC simulation via `ruin_check()` our estimator is given by
$$
\hat p = \frac{I_1 + \dots + I_n}{n}
$$
where the $I_j$'s are all i.i.d. and are the indicators of 5-year survival. Therefore, by the Central Limit Theorem this converges to a Normal distribution with mean $p = 1 - \psi_{60} (c_0)$ and standard deviation
$$
\sqrt{\frac{p(1 - p)}{n}}.
$$
By Slutsky's theorem the standard error can be approximated by
$$
\text{se}(\hat p) \approx \sqrt{\frac{\hat p (1 - \hat p)}{n}},
$$
so our pivot is 
$$
\frac{\hat p - p}{\sqrt{\hat p (1 - \hat p ) / n}} \sim \mathcal N (0,1),
$$
giving us a $95\%$ confidence interval of 
$$
\hat p - 1.96 \sqrt{\frac{\hat p (1 - \hat p)}{n}} \leq p \leq \hat p + 1.96 \sqrt{\frac{\hat p (1 - \hat p)}{n}},
$$
meaning that 
$$
\hat p - 1.96 \sqrt{\frac{\hat p (1 - \hat p)}{n}} = 0.9895 \quad \text{and} \quad \hat p + 1.96 \sqrt{\frac{\hat p (1 - \hat p)}{n}} = 0.9905
$$
Here, computation is expensive. We start with less computations to find an approximate range then increase precision. For the required precision level we need $n$ large enough such that 
$$
n \geq \left(\frac{1.96}{0.0005} \right)^2 \times 0.01 \times (1 - 0.01) = 152128,
$$
so in our final search we will use more than 150k simulations. We will define a function that simulates the probability of ruin:

```{r chunk13}

prob_ruin <- function(nsim, t, lambda, sev_distribution, shape = NULL, rate = NULL,
                      policy, d = NULL, alpha = NULL,
                      c0 = 50, theta = 0.07, xi = 0.1) {
  prob <- mean(replicate(nsim, ruin_check_reinsurance(t, lambda, sev_distribution, 
                                           shape, rate, policy, d, alpha,
                                           c0, theta, xi)))
  return(prob)
}

```

We will also define a helper to compute standard error:

```{r chunk14}

se <- function(p, n) {
  sqrt(p * (1 - p) / n)
}

```

## Finding the Target Retention Rate

From previous results, we've seen that the minimum possible value of $\alpha_{99\%}$ such that ruin is not certain is $0.3$. We've also seen that $\alpha = 0.71$ leads to a ruin probability of $0.018962$, which is much too high. So we guess that $\alpha_{99\%}$ in the range $(0.3, 0.7)$, and use this to conduct our search.

```{r chunk15}

set.seed(3162)
nsim <- 5e4

# A rough search for alpha based on an educated guess
alpha_grid_rough <- seq(alpha_min, 0.7, 0.01)
alpha_search_rough <- sapply(alpha_grid_rough, function(a) prob_ruin(nsim, 
                                               t = 60, lambda = 2, 
                                               sev_distribution = "gamma", 
                                               shape = 0.3162, rate = 0.229245, 
                                               policy = 'proportional', 
                                               alpha = a))
# Find a new range of values to search by filtering
alpha_prob_rough <- 1 - alpha_search_rough
alpha_CI_rough <- data.frame(lower = alpha_prob_rough - 
                             1.96 * se(alpha_prob_rough, nsim), 
                             upper = alpha_prob_rough + 
                             1.96 * se(alpha_prob_rough, nsim))
filter_index_rough <- which(abs(alpha_CI_rough$lower - 0.9895) < 1e-3 &
                            abs(alpha_CI_rough$upper - 0.9905) < 1e-3)
alpha_range_rough <- alpha_grid_rough[filter_index_rough]


# Final search for alpha
nsim <- 2e5

alpha_grid_fine <- seq(min(alpha_range_rough), max(alpha_range_rough), 0.001)
alpha_search_fine <- sapply(alpha_grid_fine, function(a) prob_ruin(nsim, 
                                             t = 60, lambda = 2, 
                                             sev_distribution = "gamma", 
                                             shape = 0.3162, rate = 0.229245, 
                                             policy = 'proportional', 
                                             alpha = a))
# Get the survival probabilities
alpha_prob_fine <- 1 - alpha_search_fine

# Compute confidence intervals
alpha_CI_fine <- data.frame(lower = alpha_prob_fine - 
                          1.96 * se(alpha_prob_fine, nsim), 
                          upper = alpha_prob_fine + 
                          1.96 * se(alpha_prob_fine, nsim))
# Filter
alpha_filter_index_fine <- which.min(abs(alpha_CI_fine$lower - 0.9895) +
                                     abs(alpha_CI_fine$upper - 0.9905))
alpha99 <- alpha_grid_fine[alpha_filter_index_fine]

# Display Results
profit_alpha99 <- profit_reinsurance(t = 60, lambda = 2, sev_distribution = 'gamma', 
